SEARCH IN A BINARY SEARCH TREE (BST)

You are given a Binary Search Tree (BST) and an integer X. Your task is to check whether the value X exists in the BST.

A Binary Search Tree is a tree where:
All values in the left subtree are smaller than the root
All values in the right subtree are greater than the root

INPUT FORMAT

The first line contains two integers N and X
N is the number of nodes in the BST
X is the value to be searched

The next (N - 1) lines describe the edges of the tree
Each line contains three values:
pi ci Ri

where
pi is the parent node value
ci is the child node value
Ri represents the relationship
L means ci is the left child of pi
R means ci is the right child of pi

OUTPUT FORMAT

Print YES if X exists in the BST
Otherwise, print NO

CONSTRAINTS

1 ≤ N ≤ 10000
1 ≤ pi, ci ≤ 100000
Ri is either L or R
All node values are distinct
1 ≤ X ≤ 100000

SAMPLE INPUT

7 6
4 2 L
4 6 R
2 1 L
2 3 R
6 5 L
6 7 R

SAMPLE OUTPUT

YES

EXPLANATION

The value 6 exists in the BST, so the output is YES.

class Solution {
    public static boolean searchInBST(Node root, int x) {
          if(root==null){
              return false;
          }
          if(root.val==x) {
              return true;
          }
          if(root.val>x){
              return searchInBST(root.left,x);
          }
          else{
             return searchInBST(root.right,x);
          }
    }
}
